`SDL_CreateTexture` and `SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface` are related but serve different purposes in SDL.

- `SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface`: This function creates a texture from an existing `SDL_Surface`. It's a convenient way to convert loaded image data, which is often initially in the form of a surface, into a texture that can be rendered to the screen with hardware acceleration.

- `SDL_CreateTexture`: This function creates an empty texture with a specified format, width, and height, which can be used as a target for rendering. You do not supply pixel data with this call; instead, it's typically used to create textures that are meant to be rendered to, akin to a render target. You can also manually update such a texture with pixel data if needed, using functions like `SDL_UpdateTexture`.

Here's a quick breakdown of their typical uses:

- **SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface**: Use this when you have an image file that you've loaded into memory as an `SDL_Surface`, and now you want to convert it into a texture for efficient rendering.
   ```cpp
   SDL_Surface* surface = IMG_Load("image.png");
   SDL_Texture* texture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(renderer, surface);
   SDL_FreeSurface(surface); // The surface can be freed once the texture is created.
   ```

- **SDL_CreateTexture**: Use this for creating:
  - Textures to be used as render targets (i.e., you can render to these textures with `SDL_SetRenderTarget`).
  - Blank textures that you plan to fill with pixel data at run-time.
  - Textures for procedural image generation.
   ```cpp
   // Example for creating an empty texture that is intended to be a render target
   SDL_Texture* targetTexture = SDL_CreateTexture(renderer, SDL_PIXELFORMAT_RGBA8888, 
                                                  SDL_TEXTUREACCESS_TARGET, width, height);
   ```

Both functions are important in SDL and they're not direct replacements for each other but offer different functionality. Depending on what your game engine requires, you might want to support both.

- You'll still use `SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface` to create textures from image files (loaded as surfaces).
- You'll need `SDL_CreateTexture` when you need to create textures for dynamic content, rendering to textures (useful for post-processing effects or complex scenes), or manipulating pixel data directly.

In your engine, you might consider wrapping both functionalities into your `Texture` class, so it supports textures both from image files and dynamically created ones. This can be done by adding constructors or factory methods to handle different creation scenarios:

```cpp
class Texture {
public:
    // Create a texture from an existing surface
    static Texture CreateFromSurface(const Renderer& renderer, const Surface& surface);

    // Create an empty texture with specific properties
    static Texture CreateEmpty(const Renderer& renderer, int width, int height, 
                               SDL_TextureAccess access, SDL_PixelFormatEnum format);

    // Other constructors, methods, etc.
};
```

This design will allow users of your `Texture` class to seamlessly work either way, depending on their needs, while encapsulating the underlying SDL library calls.

In game engine design, the features you implement should reflect both the present needs of your project and the expected needs of your potential users. Supporting dynamic content is not inherently "needed," but it is a feature that adds flexibility and opens up more possibilities for the types of games that can be built with your engine.

Dynamic content refers to any content that can change during the runtime of the game – this includes things like procedural textures, render-to-texture for post-processing effects, in-game video playback, or simply being able to manipulate pixels on the fly.

If your current project and target audience do not require these capabilities, then you may not need to implement them right away.

However, it's worth keeping in mind that adding these options could be beneficial in the long term. They can be added incrementally as your project evolves and as you better understand the needs of your game engine's users.

For example, even if you don't support all pixel formats or access types right away, you could provide a default and simplified interface for creating empty dynamic textures, something like this:

```cpp
class Texture {
public:
    // Existing functionality...

    // Provide a method to create an empty texture with common defaults
    static Texture CreateEmpty(const Renderer& renderer, int width, int height) {
        // Assuming a common format like RGBA and streaming access
        return SDL_CreateTexture(renderer.GetRenderer(), 
                                 SDL_PIXELFORMAT_RGBA8888, 
                                 SDL_TEXTUREACCESS_STREAMING, 
                                 width, height);
    }

    // Provide a method to update the texture's pixel data
    void Update(const void* pixelData, int pitch) {
        if (texture) {
            SDL_UpdateTexture(texture, NULL, pixelData, pitch);
        }
    }

    // Other constructors, methods, etc.
};
```

In this simplified version, `CreateEmpty` creates an empty texture with a preset format (RGBA) and access type (streaming, which allows for updates). This covers many common cases. The `Update` method is provided for updating the texture's pixel data from an external buffer; `pitch` is the length of a row of pixels in bytes.

This way, you provide the option for dynamic content without overwhelming the user with options or yourself with implementation details. Over time, you can listen to feedback from users and observe your own needs to determine if and when to expand this functionality based on demand.

As always, ensure that your API is well-documented, so users understand what features are available and how to use them. This will help keep your interface easy to understand and use, even as you provide more advanced options.

Implementing transformation and layering methods without directly exposing SDL specifics involves creating a layer of abstraction in your `Renderer` class. Here are some ways to approach this task:

### 1. Transformations:

Transformation usually refers to operations such as translation (moving), rotation, and scaling of rendered objects. To abstract away SDL notions like `SDL_RendererFlip`:

- **Create a `Transform` class (or struct) to encapsulate transformation data:** Define a data structure that stores the position, rotation, scale, and possibly orientation (flipping). This class can also hold a method to calculate a transformation matrix, if applicable.

```cpp
class Transform {
public:
    Vector2 position;
    float rotation; // In degrees
    Vector2 scale;
    bool flipHorizontal;
    bool flipVertical;

    // Other transformation-related methods
};
```

- **Add transformation methods to the `Renderer` class:** Use the `Transform` class in your rendering methods to allow users to specify how an object should be transformed when it's drawn.

```cpp
void Renderer::RenderTexture(const Texture& texture, const Transform& transform) {
    SDL_Rect destRect = { ... calculate using transform.position and transform.scale ... };
    double angle = static_cast<double>(transform.rotation);
    SDL_RendererFlip flip = static_cast<SDL_RendererFlip>(
        (transform.flipHorizontal ? SDL_FLIP_HORIZONTAL : 0x0) |
        (transform.flipVertical ? SDL_FLIP_VERTICAL : 0x0)
    );

    // Call SDL_RenderCopyEx with transformation parameters
    SDL_RenderCopyEx(
        sdlRenderer, // Your underlying SDL_Renderer
        texture.GetSDLTexture(), // Method to get SDL_Texture from your Texture class
        nullptr, // nullptr to draw the whole texture, or specify a source rect
        &destRect,
        angle,
        nullptr, // nullptr for the rotation center, or specify SDL_Point for pivot
        flip
    );
}
```

### 2. Layering:

Layering involves determining the draw order of objects, so that some objects appear on top of others. There are a few ways to handle this:

- **Simple layering using an integer 'depth' or 'z-index':** Each drawable object could have an associated depth value. Higher values are drawn later, thus appearing on top. You would need to sort your draw calls by this value before issuing them. 

```cpp
class Drawable {
public:
    int depth;
    // Other properties for rendering
};

std::vector<Drawable> drawables; // This needs to be sorted before rendering
```

- **More complex layering using render targets or render layers:** While SDL has render targets, neatly encapsulating this in your engine would require all the complications of managing multiple textures, which can be complex. Instead, you might consider implementing a 'RenderLayer' class that groups drawables together. The `RenderLayer` would manage ordering and you would render each layer in sequence.

```cpp
class RenderLayer {
public:
    void AddDrawable(const Drawable& drawable);
    void Render(Renderer& renderer); // Sorts if necessary and renders all drawables within this layer

private:
    std::vector<Drawable> drawables; // Might need ordering/sorting
};

std::vector<RenderLayer> layers; // Render in order of layer
```

In both methods, the order in which you render these sorted drawables determines the layering. The sorting itself is usually done each frame before rendering, sometimes only when drawables have changed order.

By following these approaches, you provide a game-engine-level interface to transformations and layering without needing to expose SDL-specific details. Users of your engine interact with game-engine-centric classes and methods, which are internally translated into SDL function calls.

Correct, you'll want to create an abstraction in your Renderer class that allows users to specify transformations for drawable objects (like textures). This abstraction will eventually work with `SDL_RenderCopyEx` under the hood, which supports positioning, scaling, rotating, and flipping textures.

To define transformations within your Renderer class, you should create a structure or class that encapsulates all the relevant information:

1. **Position**: Usually represented as a 2D vector containing x and y coordinates.
2. **Scale**: Can be represented as a 2D vector where each component corresponds to the scaling factor in the x and y directions.
3. **Rotation**: Typically represented as a float containing the angle of rotation in degrees.
4. **Flip**: Ability to flip the texture horizontally and/or vertically. This can be represented by a simple enumeration.

Here's an example of how you might define a `Transform` data structure:

```cpp
struct Vector2 {
    float x, y;
};

enum class Flip {
    None = 0,
    Horizontal = 1,
    Vertical = 2
};

struct Transform {
    Vector2 position;
    Vector2 scale;
    float rotation; // In degrees
    Flip flip;

    Transform()
        : position({0, 0}), scale({1, 1}), rotation(0), flip(Flip::None) {}
};
```

Now, in your Renderer class, you can define a method that accepts a texture and a transform object, calculates the SDL parameters, and calls `SDL_RenderCopyEx`:

```cpp
class Renderer {
public:
    void RenderTexture(const Texture& texture, const Transform& transform) {
        SDL_Rect srcRect; // Define the source rectangle if needed
        SDL_Rect dstRect; // Define the destination rectangle based on transform.position and transform.scale

        dstRect.x = static_cast<int>(transform.position.x);
        dstRect.y = static_cast<int>(transform.position.y);
        dstRect.w = static_cast<int>(texture.GetWidth() * transform.scale.x);
        dstRect.h = static_cast<int>(texture.GetHeight() * transform.scale.y);

        SDL_RendererFlip sdlFlip = SDL_FLIP_NONE;
        if (transform.flip == Flip::Horizontal) {
            sdlFlip = SDL_RendererFlip(sdlFlip | SDL_FLIP_HORIZONTAL);
        }
        if (transform.flip == Flip::Vertical) {
            sdlFlip = SDL_RendererFlip(sdlFlip | SDL_FLIP_VERTICAL);
        }

        // Assuming you've got a method GetSDLTexture() for getting SDL_Texture from your Texture wrapper
        SDL_Texture* sdlTexture = texture.GetSDLTexture();

        // Call SDL_RenderCopyEx with the parameters calculated from the Transform
        SDL_RenderCopyEx(
            internalSDLRenderer, // Your SDL_Renderer
            sdlTexture,
            &srcRect, // or nullptr to use the entire texture
            &dstRect,
            static_cast<double>(transform.rotation),
            nullptr, // null for rotation center or you can specify an SDL_Point
            sdlFlip
        );
    }

private:
    SDL_Renderer* internalSDLRenderer; // SDL_Renderer handle
};
```

With `Transform` being a data structure encapsulating the concept of transformations, it becomes easy to add properties to entities or other drawable objects later on in development. Then, when you add entities to your engine, they can hold an instance of `Transform` to represent their own position, scale, rotation, and flipping state within the world.

By providing this abstraction layer now, you'll make it easier to extend your engine while maintaining a clear and understandable interface.

