public:
    Camera() : position(0, 0), zoom(1), rotation(0) {}

    void SetPosition(float x, float y) { position.x = x; position.y = y; }
    void SetZoom(float zoomFactor) { zoom = zoomFactor; }
    void SetRotation(float angleDegrees) { rotation = angleDegrees; }
    // Additional methods to move or adjust the camera...

    FPoint GetPosition() const { return position; }
    float GetZoom() const { return zoom; }
    float GetRotation() const { return rotation; }

private:
    FPoint position;
    float zoom;
    float rotation;
};
```

This Camera class could then interact with your Renderer in the following ways:

- When you render a scene, you adjust all draw calls to take into account the camera's position and zoom. For example, before drawing anything, you translate all coordinates by the negative of the camera's position and scale by the inverse of the camera's zoom factor.
- Your Renderer class might have methods to set and use a camera, translating and scaling the draw calls as needed.

A camera system can be as simple or complex as your game engine needs it to be, and it can evolve over time. Starting simple and iterating based on your needs is a common and effective strategy for game engine development.

